Yes — and the cleanest version is not “one app that nags you,” but a consumer-side pricing shield plus a merchant-side compliance layer.

Call it FairPrice.

Core idea

FairPrice sits between the buyer and the seller and tries to make every purchase look like it’s coming from a neutral, low-information customer profile, so the seller cannot quietly change price based on your income, neighborhood, device, browsing history, urgency, or past behavior.

That matters because the FTC said in January 2025 that companies in its surveillance-pricing study were using personal data and AI-driven systems to tailor prices, with examples including precise location, browsing behavior, and other consumer signals.  ￼

What it would do

1. Mask the signals sellers use

The app/browser layer would:
	•	strip tracking parameters
	•	block third-party pricing scripts where possible
	•	rotate browser fingerprints
	•	normalize device/user-agent signals
	•	hide high-value signals like location precision
	•	offer a “clean-room checkout” mode

The point is not anonymity for its own sake. The point is price neutrality.

2. Run multi-profile price checks

Before you buy, the app quietly tests the same item through several “personas”:
	•	logged in vs logged out
	•	iPhone vs desktop
	•	home IP vs relay
	•	affluent ZIP proxy vs neutral region
	•	repeat visitor vs first-time visitor

If the price changes materially, it shows:
	•	Displayed price
	•	Lowest observed neutral price
	•	Discrimination confidence
	•	Likely factors used

3. Give you a fairness score

Each seller gets a live score such as:
	•	Green: consistent pricing
	•	Yellow: mild variation
	•	Red: likely surveillance pricing

The FTC’s study and issue spotlight both describe concern that firms may be using data-driven systems to change prices at the individual level, which is exactly the behavior this score is trying to detect and surface.  ￼

4. Auto-negotiate toward the neutral price

If a higher price is detected, the app can try:
	•	reloading through neutral mode
	•	clearing session identifiers
	•	switching to guest checkout
	•	changing fulfillment path
	•	using a relay region
	•	replaying from a clean browser state

5. Produce evidence

For the user, it saves a compact audit trail:
	•	timestamp
	•	product
	•	price variants observed
	•	session conditions
	•	screenshots/hash proofs
	•	which signals correlated with price movement

That gives a consumer something more useful than a feeling of being gouged.

