The stronger version: a two-sided system

The best real-world design is:

Consumer app: FairPrice Shield

Protects buyers from covert price discrimination.

Producer API: FairPrice Verify

Lets merchants prove they are not using protected or exploitative inputs for individualized pricing.

That second side matters because some price differences are legitimate, like inventory, shipping, or taxes. The merchant layer would separate:

Allowed variables
	•	inventory
	•	shipping cost
	•	time-limited public promotions
	•	region-level tax/regulatory differences

Blocked variables
	•	inferred income
	•	credit profile proxies
	•	neighborhood affluence
	•	urgency/vulnerability inference
	•	detailed browsing history
	•	cross-site tracking data
	•	device-price stereotypes

The FTC has publicly highlighted concern over the use of personal data and machine learning for individualized pricing, and the CFPB has separately proposed limits on how sensitive consumer and financial data can be sold or shared by data brokers.  ￼

